target.echo:
Project name: ${ant.project.name} Ant version: ${ant.version} Java version: ${ant.java.version}
Instruction: 1. To build the whole thing, go to 'src' directory which contains build.xml (see also Item 3 below) then type this command: $ ant build After this, the final output file, ${product.name}.jar, will be created at build/jar. You have to copy it to dist/${product.name} manually. For automatic replacing, try this: $ ant build-replace 2. To just compile the project, type this: $ ant compile To run the program (after the compilation is done successfully), type this: $ ant run To make the output jar, then, type this: $ ant jar To create the program's javadoc, type this: $ ant javadoc For more information about other specific tasks, type this: $ ant -p OR $ ant -projecthelp 3. Before the compilation will succeed, the file structure has to be arranged in this way (at least):
ROOT-DIR/ (You name it) |--src/ | |--main/ | | |--paliplatform/ | | | |--*.java | | |--module-info.java | |--resources/ | | |--fonts/ | | |--images/ | | |--js/ | | |--styles/ | | |--text/ | |--build.xml | |--manifest.txt | |--dist/ (containing the final product) | |--${product.name} | |--data/ | |--fonts/ | |--lib/ | |--util/ | |--${product.name}.jar | |--some other files... | |--build/ (created and deleted in the process) | |--classes/ | |--jar/ | |--javadoc/ | |...
